article.description: Freshman Sylvia Fowles scored 13 points and grabbed nine rebounds to help No. 1 LSU shake off a slow start to beat South Carolina 66-36 on Sunday.
article.headline: LSU easily tops South Carolina
article.linkText: LSU moves one step closer to first SEC title
article.story:
Freshman Sylvia Fowles scored 13 points
and grabbed nine rebounds to help No. 1 LSU shake off a slow start
to beat South Carolina 66-36 on Sunday.
	   The Lady Tigers (23-1, 10-0 Southeastern Conference) won their
10th straight after scoring the first 24 points of the second half
to turn a seven-point game at the break into a blowout.
	   It was another woeful game for the Gamecocks (6-18, 0-10 SEC),
who notched the lowest point total in coach Susan Walvius' eight
years. South Carolina shot 31.3 percent (15-of-48) and had 28
turnovers.
	   With the win, the Lady Tigers got a step closer to their first
SEC regular-season title and also closed in on becoming the first
team other than Tennessee to win the league title outright since
Georgia in 1997.
	   When the game started Sunday, LSU may have been still enjoying
last Thursday's 68-58 win over the No. 5 Lady Vols. The Lady Tigers
missed 13 of their first 19 shots, including several open
3-pointers, to fall behind 14-10.
	   With the outside game struggling, LSU started pounding the ball
inside, ending the first half on a 16-5 run with the lead into the
break.
	   The Lady Tigers outscored South Carolina 36-16 in the paint.
	   Seimone Augustus scored LSU's first six points, but finished
with just 13, seven below her season average. Scholanda Hoston had
11. LSU has beaten South Carolina eight straight times.
	   Stacy Booker led South Carolina with 15 points. No other
Gamecock scored more than four points or got more than five
rebounds.
	   The Gamecocks have now lost 16 straight SEC games and are in
danger of becoming the first team to go winless in the league since
South Carolina went 0-14 in Walvius' second year in 1999.
